There are a handful of typography errors that get made again and again. They're not taste issues, they’re “why does my app look like a ransom note?” issues. Here are the repeat offenders and how to fix them.

### Problem 1: Invisible Text

Light weight, small size, pale color on white. Nobody with less-than-perfect vision can read this. Don't use light gray for important content.

Fix: Use regular weight minimum, 14px or larger, and darker gray.

### Crime 2: Justified Text on the Web

Justified text creates awkward spaces between words and makes paragraphs look broken. Browsers aren't books.

Fix: Left-align body text. Always.

### Crime 3: All-Caps Body Text

Reading all-caps takes 10–13% longer. It's like shouting in a monotone.

Fix: Use all-caps only for short labels (2–4 words), badges, and category tags. Never for paragraphs.

### Crime 4: No Type Hierarchy

Everything the same size and weight means nothing stands out. It's a choir where everyone sings the same note.

Fix: Use a type scale with at least 3–4 different size/weight combinations.

### Crime 5: Decorative Fonts for Body

That handwritten or display font you love? Gorgeous at 48px in a hero. At 14px in a paragraph, it’s a migraine.

Fix: Use personality fonts for headlines only. Pair with a readable sans-serif for body.

### Crime 6: Tight Line Height

Default line height is fine for headlines. For body text, it's a wall of words.

Fix: Use 1.6 or higher line height for all body text.

